n Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie]]\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">''[[All the Way (film)|All the Way]]''</div>\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Melissa Leo}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{iobdb name|2622}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Melissa Leo\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestSupportingActress 2001-2020}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{EmmyAward ComedyGuestActress}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestSuppActressMotionPicture 2001-2020}}\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor}}\n{{IndependentSpiritBestFemaleLead 2000\u20132020}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward FemaleSupportMotionPicture}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leo, Melissa}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead winners]]\n[[Category:People from the Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award winners]]\n[[Category:State University of New York at Purchase alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Method actors]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox actor\n| name        = Melissa Leo\n| image       = Melissa Leo at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg\n| caption     = Leo at the 2009 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_name  = Melissa Leo\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1960|9|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], New York, U.S.\n| years active = 1984\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actress \n| residence   = [[Stone Ridge, New York]], U.S.\n| partner     =\n| children    = 1\n| relatives   = [[Christine Leo Roussel]]<br>(paternal aunt)\n}}\n\n'''Melissa Leo''' (born September 14, 1960)<!--STOP!: AWARDS DON'T BELONG HERE--> is an American actress. She is the recipient of several accolades, including an [[Academy Award]], a [[Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy Award]], a [[Golden Globe Award]], two [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]]<!--Main body says nominated for one Movie and one TV Award, but no wins--> and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]].\n\nAfter appearing on several television shows and films in the 1980s, Leo became a regular on the television shows ''[[All My Children]],'' which won her a [[Daytime Emmy Award]], and ''[[The Young Riders]]''. Her breakthrough role came in 1993 as detective and later sergeant [[Kay Howard]] on the television series ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'' (1993\u20131997).\n\nLeo received critical acclaim for her performance as Ray Eddy in the 2008 film ''[[Frozen River]]'', earning her several nominations and awards, including an Academy Award nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]. In 2010, Leo won several awards for her performance as Alice Eklund-Ward in the film ''[[The Fighter]]'', including the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]].\n\nIn 2013, she won a Primetime Emmy Award for her guest role on the television series ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]''. She starred in the 2015 Fox event series ''[[Wayward Pines]]'' as Nurse Pam. She then starred in the 2017 [[Netflix]] film ''[[The Most Hated Woman in America]]'' as [[American Atheists]] founder [[Madalyn Murray O'Hair]].\n\n==Early life==\nLeo was born in [[Manhattan]] and grew up on the [[Lower East Side]].<ref name=oscar1>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123507540420025655?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Veteran Actors, First Time Nominees |work=Wall Street Journal |date=2009-02-19 |accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref> She is the daughter of Margaret ([[n\u00e9e]] Chessington), a [[California]]-born teacher, and Arnold Leo III, an editor at [[Grove Press]], fisherman, and former spokesman for the [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton]] Baymen's Association. She has one brother, Erik Leo.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lambert|first1=Pam|title=She's All Right Jack|url=http://people.com/archive/shes-all-right-jack-vol-44-no-23/|accessdate=July 22, 2017|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=December 4, 1995}}</ref> Her aunt is art historian [[Christine Leo Roussel]].<ref>[http://www.rousselartconservation.com/about.html Roussel art website] retrieved 3/7/2015</ref> Leo's parents divorced, and her mother moved them to Red Clover Commune, in [[Putney, Vermont]].\n\nLeo began performing as a child with the [[Bread and Puppet Theater]] Company. She attended [[Bellows Falls High School]] in [[Bellows Falls, Vermont]], and studied acting at [[Mountview Academy of Theatre Arts]] in London and [[State University of New York at Purchase|SUNY Purchase]], but did not graduate, choosing to leave school and move to New York City to begin auditioning for acting jobs.<ref>[http://thehollywoodinterview.blogspot.com/2009/01/best-actress-nominee-melissa-leo.html Melissa Leo interview] retrieved 3/8/2015</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsday.com/news/printedition/longisland/ny-lileo226045011feb22,0,3078015.story |title=Actress up for Oscar has longtime ties to Hamptons |work=Newsday |date=2009-02-21 |accessdate=2011-01-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225100619/http://www.newsday.com/news/printedition/longisland/ny-lileo226045011feb22,0,3078015.story |archive-date=2009-02-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/95/Melissa-Leo.html |title=Melissa Leo Biography (1960\u2013) |website=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref><ref>Mother's California birth stated on the ''[[68th Golden Globe Awards]]'', January 16, 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/doc/278257673.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan%2025,%201990&author=By%20Michele%20Ingrassia&pub=Newsday%20(Combined%20editions)&edition=&startpage=&desc=The%20Unlikely%20Bayman%20Arnold%20Leo%20forsook%20Manhattan%20years%20ago%20for%20the%20East%20End.%20Today,%20he's%20the%20single%20most%20powerful%20voice%20for%20that%20endangered%20species,%20the%20Long%20Island%20fisherman | work=Newsday | first=Michele | last=Ingrassia | title=The Unlikely Bayman Arnold Leo forsook Manhattan years ago for the East End. Today, he's the single most powerful voice for that endangered species, the Long Island fisherman | date=January 25, 1990}}</ref> Leo spent summers at her father's house in Springs, a section of [[East Hampton, New York]].<ref name=oscar1/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=200990122055 | title=Vermonter Nominated | website=Burlington Free Press | date=January 23, 2009}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLeo's acting debut came in 1984, for which she was nominated for a [[Daytime Emmy]] at the [[12th Daytime Emmy Awards]] for Outstanding Ingenue/Woman in a Drama Series for ''[[All My Children]]''. Following this, Leo appeared in several films, including the lead role as a straitlaced girl named Cookie who succumbed to prostitution in ''[[Streetwalkin']]'', ''[[A Time of Destiny (film)|A Time of Destiny]]'', ''[[Last Summer in the Hamptons]]'', and ''[[Venice/Venice]].'' She also had several appearances on television, most notably her role as [[Kay Howard|Det. Sgt. Kay Howard]] on ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'' until 1997. Three years later she reprised her role in the television movie, ''[[Homicide: The Movie]]''. After a brief hiatus from acting, Leo's breakthrough came three years later in the [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]] film, ''[[21 Grams]]'' released to critical acclaim. Leo appeared in a supporting role alongside [[Sean Penn]], [[Naomi Watts]], [[Benicio del Toro]], and [[Clea DuVall]]. Leo shared a Best Ensemble Acting award from the Phoenix Film Critics Society in 2003 and the runner-up for the [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association]] for Best Supporting Actress.\n\n[[File:Melissa Leo.jpg|thumb|150px|Leo in January 2006|left]]\n\nLeo appeared in supporting roles throughout the 2000s including the film ''[[Hide and Seek (2005 film)|Hide and Seek]]'', the independent film ''[[American Gun (2005 film)|American Gun]]'', both in 2005, and a minor role in the comedy ''[[Mr. Woodcock]]''. In 2006, she won the [[Bronze Wrangler]] at the Western Heritage Awards for Outstanding Theatrical Motion Picture for ''[[The Three Burials of Melquiades Estrada]]'' shared with [[Tommy Lee Jones]] who also produced the film. In 2008, she won the Maverick Actor Award and also the Best Actress award at the Method Fest for ''Lullaby'' (2008).\n\nThat same year, Leo earned critical praise for her performance in the film ''[[Frozen River]]'', winning several awards, including the Best Actress award from the [[Independent Spirit Awards]], the Spotlight award from the [[National Board of Review]], and Best Actress nominations from the [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]], [[Broadcast Film Critics Association]], and [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Awards]]. Critic [[Roger Ebert]] backed her for a win, stating: \"Best Actress: Melissa Leo. What a complete performance, evoking a woman's life in a time of economic hardship. The most timely of films, but that isn't reason enough. I was struck by how intensely determined she was to make the payments, support her two children, carry on after her abandonment by a gambling husband, and still maintain rules and goals around the house. This was a heroic woman.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Roger Ebert |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090127/OSCARS/901279994 |title=Elevating the Oscar winners, Part #3: Best Leading Actress |work=Chicago Sun-Times |date=2011-04-23 |accessdate=2011-04-23}}</ref>\n\nFollowing ''Frozen River'', Leo continued to appear in several independent films, and had a minor role in the 2008 film ''[[Righteous Kill]]'', with [[Al Pacino]] and her ''Hide and Seek'' co-star, [[Robert De Niro]]. Leo appeared in a series of films throughout 2009, including ''[[According to Greta]]'', the title character in ''[[Stephanie's Image]]'', ''[[True Adolescents]]'', and ''[[Veronika Decides to Die (film)|Veronika Decides to Die]]''.\n\n[[File:Melissa Leo at 81st Academy Awards.JPG|thumb|213x213px|Melissa Leo at [[81st Academy Awards]]]]\nIn 2010, Leo received fame for her role in [[David O. Russell]]'s ''[[The Fighter]]''. Rick Bentley of ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' said: \"Both actors ([[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Christian Bale]]) are very good, but they get blown off the screen by Melissa Leo, who plays their mother, Alice Ward. Leo's Oscar-worthy portrayal of Alice as a master manipulator goes beyond acting to a total transformation.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2010/12/18/1918252/cast-puts-punch-in-scrappy-fighter.html |title=Cast puts punch in scrappy 'Fighter' |publisher=CharlotteObserver.com |date=2010-12-18 |accessdate=2011-01-18 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] referred to it as a \"teeth-gratingly brilliant performance.\" Leo and several of the film's actors including her co-star [[Amy Adams]] and Bale were nominated. For her performance Leo received several awards, including the [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]], [[Dallas-Fort Worth Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress|Dallas-Fort Worth Film Critics Association]], [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actress|New York Film Critics Circle]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Screen Actors Guild]], and culminating in her winning the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]. While accepting her Oscar, Leo said: \"When I watched [[Kate Winslet|Kate]] two years ago, it looked so fucking easy!\" She apologized afterwards for using profanity, admitting that it was \"a very inappropriate place to use that particular word ... those words, I apologize to anyone that they offend\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/celebritology/2011/02/melissa_leo_drops_the_f-bomb_i.html| author= Liz Kelly |title=Melissa Leo drops F-bomb in Oscar Acceptance Speech|publisher=The Washington Post |date=February 27, 2011 |accessdate=February 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/movie-guide/OSCARS+Bomb+mars+Melissa+speech/4356254/story.html| title=OSCARS: F-Bomb mars speech; Toy Story 3, In a Better World, Christian Bale, Social Network. King's Speech take awards |author=Vancouver Sun and wire services |publisher=[[The Vancouver Sun]] |date=February 27, 2011 |accessdate=February 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her win, Leo had created some controversy by attempting to self-promote her Oscar campaign, rather than rely on the marketing department of the studio. Leo personally bought ad space in Hollywood trade publications, which was initially thought might backfire in a similar manner to previous Oscar contenders [[Chill Wills]] and [[Margaret Avery]].<ref>[http://theweek.com/article/index/212045/melissa-leos-rogue-oscar-campaign Melissa Leo's 'rogue' Oscar campaign]. The Week (2011-02-11). Retrieved on 2013-07-13.</ref>\n\nFollowing her Oscar win, Leo appeared in the [[HBO]] miniseries ''[[Mildred Pierce (miniseries)|Mildred Pierce]]'' alongside [[Kate Winslet]], [[Evan Rachel Wood]] and [[Guy Pearce]]. Her performance garnered an [[Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie]]. Her next projects include the satirical horror film ''[[Red State (2011 film)|Red State]]'', the independent comedy ''[[Why Stop Now (film)|Predisposed]]'' with [[Jesse Eisenberg]] currently in pre-production<ref>{{cite web| url=http://upandcomers.net/2011/03/02/jesse-eisenberg-to-play-melissa-leos-son-in-predisposed/ | title=Jesse Eisenberg to play Melissa Leo's son in \"Predisposed |author=Vancouver Sun and wire services |publisher=Up and Comers |date=March 2, 2011 |accessdate=March 2, 2011}}</ref> and the crime thriller ''[[The Dead Circus]]'' based on the novel by John Kaye with [[Michael C. Hall]] and [[James Marsden]] currently in development.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-oscar-winners-are-doing-163950/| title=What Oscar Winners Are Doing Next|author=Jay A. Fernandez |publisher=Hollywood Reporter|date=March 3, 2011 |accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref> She guest-starred in an episode of the hit [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] comedy ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]'', which garnered her an Emmy win for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series.\n\nLeo appeared in the action-thriller ''[[Olympus Has Fallen]]'' as Ruth McMillan, the Secretary of Defense who was held hostage by terrorists in the White House and ''[[Oblivion (2013 film)|Oblivion]]'' as the main antagonist. She reprised her role in the ''Olympus'' sequel ''[[London Has Fallen]]''.\n\nLeo appeared in supporting roles in the thriller films ''[[Prisoners (2013 film)|Prisoners]]'', ''[[The Equalizer (film)|The Equalizer]]'', and ''[[The Equalizer 2]]'', having previously appeared in a 1985 episode of the [[The Equalizer|original series]]. Leo appeared on the Fox series ''[[Wayward Pines]]'' as Nurse Pam.\n\n==Personal life==\nLeo lives in [[Stone Ridge, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omaha.com/index.php?u_page=2620&u_sid=10570078 |title=Nebraska threads woven into red carpet |publisher=Omaha.com |date= |accessdate=2011-01-18 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1987, she had a son, John Matthew \"Jack\" Heard, with her former boyfriend, actor [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]]. She considers director [[Adam Davenport]] a \"son of sorts.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/doree/how-melissa-leo-became-an-overnight-sensation-in-just-30-yea|title=How Melissa Leo Became An Overnight Sensation In Just 30 Years|last=Shafrir|first=Doree|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\nLeo publicly rejected the label of feminist in statements made during a 2012 interview with ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'': \"I don't think of myself as a feminist at all. As soon as we start labeling and categorizing ourselves and others, that's going to shut down the world. I would never say that.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/08/16/melissa_leo_im_no_feminist/|title=Melissa Leo: \"I'm no feminist\"|date=August 17, 2012|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> She reiterated these sentiments in a 2017 interview.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/03/20/the-most-hated-woman-in-america-melissa-leo-on-the-murder-of-atheist-madalyn-murray-o-hair.html|title='The Most Hated Woman in America': Melissa Leo on the Murder of Atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair|date=March 21, 2017|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''Always''\n| Peggy\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Streetwalkin']]''\n| Cookie\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Deadtime Stories (film)|Deadtime Stories]]''\n| Judith \"MaMa\" Baer\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''{{sortname|A|Time of Des