{"title_page": "Antonio Francesco Grazzini", "text_new": "[[File:Anton Francesco Grazzini.jpg|thumb|Antonio Francesco Grazzini]]\n[[File:Pale degli accademici della crusca, lasca (antonio francesco grazzini), xix secolo, pesce che guizza.jpg|thumb|The shovel of Anton Francesco Grazzini (il Lasca) at the [[Accademia della Crusca]]]]\n\n'''Antonio Francesco Grazzini''' or '''Antonfrancisco Grazzini''' (March 22, 1503{{snd}}February 18, 1584) was an [[Italian people|Italian]] author.<ref name=eb9>\"{{Cite EB9|wstitle=Grazzini, Antonfrancesco|volume=XI}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born at [[Florence]] or in {{Interlanguage link multi|Staggia Senese|it}} (he wrote of himself: ''{{lang|it|Io sono a Staggia, ch'\u00e8 la patria mia, e de' miei primi l'antica magione\u2026}}''<ref>''Rime di Antonfrancesco detto il Lasca'', parte prima, Stamperia di Francesco Moucke, Firenze 1741, pag. XXI.</ref>) of a good family, but there is no record of his upbringing and education. He probably began to practise as an [[apothecary]] as a youth; and owned the then famous [[Farmacia del Moro, Florence|Farmacia del Moro]] near the Cathedral. In 1540 he was among the founders of the Accademia degli Umidi, which was soon renamed [[Accademia Fiorentina]]. He later took a leading role in the establishment of the more famous [[Accademia della Crusca]], which published his ''Vocabulario'' of words accepted as the [[Italian language|purest Italian]]. To both societies he was known as '''Il Lasca''' or '''Leuciscus''', a [[pseudonym]] which is still frequently substituted for his proper name.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n\nGrazzini was temperamental, his life consequently enlivened or disturbed by various literary quarrels. His Umidi brethren expelled him for a time, because of his ruthless criticism of the Arameans, a party of academicians who maintained that the [[Florentine language]] was derived from [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Aramaic]], or some other branch of the Semitic. He was readmitted in 1566, when his friend Salviati was consul.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n\nII Lasca ranks as one of the great masters of Tuscan prose. His style is flexible and abundantly idiomatic, but without affectation. It has the force and freshness of popular speech, whilst retaining a flavour of academic culture.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n\n==Main works==\n*''Le Cene'' (1549), a collection of stories in the manner of [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Boccaccio]], and a number of prose comedies. One of the stories is ''The Story of Doctor Manente'', translated and with an introduction by [[D.H. Lawrence]] ([[G. Orioli]], 1929) {{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n*''La Gelosia'' (1568)\n*''La Spiritata'' (1561)\n*''I Parentadi''\n*''La Arenga''\n*''La Sibilla''\n*''La Pinzochera''\n*''L'Arzigogolo''\n\nA number of miscellaneous poems, a few letters and ''Four Orations to the Cross'' complete the list of Grazzini's works.\n\nHe also edited the works of [[Francesco Berni]], and collected ''Tutti I trionfi, larri, mascherate o canti carnascialeschi, andati per Firenze dal tempo del [[Lorenzo de' Medici|Magnifico Lorenzo vecchio de 'Medici]] fino all'anno 1559'' (the latter influenced [[Goethe]]'s \"[[Faust: The Second Part of the Tragedy|Faust]]\"). In 1868 [[Adamo Rossi]] published in his ''Ricerche per le biblioteche di Perugia'' three novelle by Grazzini, from a manuscript of the 16th century in the Comunale of Perugia; and in 1870 a small collection of those poems which have been left unpublished by previous editors appeared at Poggibonsi, ''Alcune poesie inedite''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911 |wstitle=Grazzini, Antonio Francesco |volume=12|page=396 }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grazzini, Antonio Francesco}}\n[[Category:1503 births]]\n[[Category:1584 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:Italian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Anton Francesco Grazzini.jpg|thumb|Antonio Francesco Grazzini]]\n[[File:Pale degli accademici della crusca, lasca (antonio francesco grazzini), xix secolo, pesce che guizza.jpg|thumb|The shovel of Anton Francesco Grazzini (il Lasca) at the [[Accademia della Crusca]]]]\n\n'''Antonio Francesco Grazzini''' or '''Antonfrancisco Grazzini''' (March 22, 1503{{snd}}February 18, 1584) was an [[Italian people|Italian]] author.<ref name=eb9>\"{{Cite EB9|wstitle=Grazzini, Antonfrancesco|volume=XI}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born at [[Florence]] or in {{Interlanguage link multi|Staggia Senese|it}} (he wrote of himself: ''{{lang|it|Io sono a Staggia, ch'\u00e8 la patria mia, e de' miei primi l'antica magione\u2026}}''<ref>''Rime di Antonfrancesco detto il Lasca'', parte prima, Stamperia di Francesco Moucke, Firenze 1741, pag. XXI.</ref>) of a good family, but there is no record of his upbringing and education. He probably began to practise as an [[apothecary]] as a youth; and owned the then famous [[Farmacia del Moro, Florence|Farmacia del Moro]] near the Cathedral. In 1540 he was among the founders of the Accademia degli Umidi, which was soon renamed [[Accademia Fiorentina]]. He later took a leading role in the establishment of the more famous [[Accademia della Crusca]], which published his ''Vocabulario'' of words accepted as the [[Italian language|purest Italian]]. To both societies he was known as '''Il Lasca''' or '''Leuciscus''', a [[pseudonym]] which is still frequently substituted for his proper name.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n\nGrazzini was temperamental, his life consequently enlivened or disturbed by various literary quarrels. His Umidi brethren expelled him for a time, because of his ruthless criticism of the Arameans, a party of academicians who maintained that the [[Florentine language]] was derived from [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Aramaic]], or some other branch of the Semitic. He was readmitted in 1566, when his friend Salviati was consul.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n\nII Lasca ranks as one of the great masters of Tuscan prose. His style is flexible and abundantly idiomatic, but without affectation. It has the force and freshness of popular speech, whilst retaining a flavour of academic culture.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n\n==Main works==\n*''Le Cene'' (1549), a collection of stories in the manner of [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Boccaccio]], and a number of prose comedies:{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=369}}\n*''La Gelosia'' (1568)\n*''La Spiritata'' (1561)\n*''I Parentadi''\n*''La Arenga''\n*''La Sibilla''\n*''La Pinzochera''\n*''L'Arzigogolo''\n\nA number of miscellaneous poems, a few letters and ''Four Orations to the Cross'' complete the list of Grazzini's works.\n\nHe also edited the works of [[Francesco Berni]], and collected ''Tutti I trionfi, larri, mascherate o canti carnascialeschi, andati per Firenze dal tempo del [[Lorenzo de' Medici|Magnifico Lorenzo vecchio de 'Medici]] fino all'anno 1559'' (the latter influenced [[Goethe]]'s \"[[Faust: The Second Part of the Tragedy|Faust]]\"). In 1868 [[Adamo Rossi]] published in his ''Ricerche per le biblioteche di Perugia'' three novelle by Grazzini, from a manuscript of the 16th century in the Comunale of Perugia; and in 1870 a small collection of those poems which have been left unpublished by previous editors appeared at Poggibonsi, ''Alcune poesie inedite''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911 |wstitle=Grazzini, Antonio Francesco |volume=12|page=396 }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grazzini, Antonio Francesco}}\n[[Category:1503 births]]\n[[Category:1584 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:Italian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Maurice Magnus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMain works:added reference to The Story of Doctor Manente", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Francesco_Grazzini"}
{"title_page": "Laura Muntz Lyall", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour = \n| name        = Laura Muntz Lyall\n| image       = Photo of Laura Muntz Lyall.jpg \n| caption     =  \n| birth_name  = Laura Adeline Muntz\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1860|6|18|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = Leamington Spa, Warwickshire, United Kingdom\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1930|12|9|1860|6|18|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = Toronto, Ontario, Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| education   = Ontario School of Art, Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi\n| spouse      = Charles W.B. Lyall\n| field       = Painting\n| training    = \n| movement    = [[Impressionism]]\n}}\n\n'''Laura Muntz Lyall''' ([[Leamington Spa, Warwickshire]], June 18, 1860 &ndash; [[Toronto]] December 9, 1930) was a Canadian impressionist painter, known for her portrayal of women and children.<ref name=CWAHI>{{cite web|title=LYALL, Laura Muntz|work=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=38|publisher=Concordia University|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nBorn '''Laura Adeline Muntz''' at Leamington Spa, [[Warwickshire]], [[England]] in 1860,{{sfn|Murray|2012|p=133}} her family emigrated to Canada when she was a child.<ref name=\"FromWomensEyes\">{{cite book|last1=Farr|first1=Dorothy|last2=Luckyj|first2=Natalie|title=From Women's Eyes: Women Painters in Canada|date=1975|publisher=Agnes Etherington Art Centre|location=Kingston|pages=28}}</ref> She grew up on a farm in the [[Muskoka|Muskoka District]] of [[Ontario]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> As a young woman, Muntz`s interest in art led to her take lessons in painting from [[William Charles Forster]] of Hamilton and to live and work at his school.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /><ref name=Prakesh /> Starting in 1882, she began to take classes at the [[OCAD_University#History|Ontario School of Art]] where she studied with [[Lucius Richard O'Brien]], and later under [[George Agnew Reid]].<ref name=Prakesh>{{cite book | title=Independent Spirit: Early Canadian Women Artists | publisher=Firefly Books | author=Prakash, A.K. | year=2008 | location=Buffalo, New York | pages=265\u2013268 | isbn=1554074177}}</ref> She studied briefly at the South Kensington School of Art in 1887, then returned to Canada to continue her studies with Reid.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> In 1891, she embarked on a seven-year period of study in Paris, attending the renowned [[Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi]]. Her preferred subject was children and she imbued scenes of them \"with spontaneity and freshness....\" <ref>Murray 2012, p. 19.</ref> From 1893 on, her handling  of paint was impressionist and she \"lightened her palette and loosened her brushwork - everything is abbreviated in swift, loose strokes.\" <ref>Murray 2012, p. 19.</ref> Her work was exhibited in various exhibitions, resulting in some works being reproduced in periodicals, prestige and successful sales.<ref>Murray 2012, p.19.</ref> \n\nTo stretch her limited financial resources, she gave private English lessons, and shared an apartment with the American painter, Wilhelmina Hawley (1860-1958). <ref>Murray 2012, p. 19-21.</ref> Hawley likely taught Muntz her \"splash and dash\" watercolour technique <ref>Murray 2012, p.22</ref> and they travelled together to Rijsoord in the southern Netherlands where they painted.<ref>Murray 2012, p.22.</ref>\n\nOn her return to Canada in 1898, she set up a studio in [[Toronto]] and began to take students.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" />  In 1906, she moved to Montreal to continue her career at 6 Beaver Hall Square.<ref name=Prakesh />\n\nHer work received recognition both in Canada and beyond. Muntz exhibited her work at the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Palace of Fine Arts]] at the 1893 [[World's Columbian Exposition]] in [[Chicago]], Illinois,<ref name=\"Nichols\">{{cite web |last1=Nichols |first1=K. L. |title=Women's Art at the World's Columbian Fair & Exposition, Chicago 1893| url=http://arcadiasystems.org/academia/cassatt9e.html#lyall|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> and then in 1894 as part of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Artistes Fran\u00e7ais]] in Paris.  She continued to exhibit at many international exhibitions following her return from Paris, and her work was recognized with a silver medal at the 1901 [[Pan-American Exposition]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\">{{Cite book|title = The Woman as Artist and as Subject in Canadian Painting|last = Gualtieri|first = Julia|publisher = Queen's University|year = 1989|isbn = |location = Kingston, Ontario|pages = 145\u2013146, 155\u2013161}}</ref> She was subsequently awarded a bronze medal at the 1904 [[Louisiana Purchase Exposition|St Louis World Fair Exposition]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /><ref name=Prakesh /> She showed 27 paintings with the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts between 1893 and 1929.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" />  Her work was frequently compared and contrasted with that of her contemporary and friend [[Florence Carlyle]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> Both the [[National Gallery of Canada]] and the [[Art Gallery of Ontario]] include her works in their holdings.<ref name=CWAHI />\n\nShe was elected as an associate member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]<ref name=\"RCA1880\">{{cite web|title=Members since 1880|url=http://rca-arc.ca/who-we-are/members/members-since-1880/|publisher=Royal Canadian Academy of Arts|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> in 1896, only the eighth woman to receive this honour.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> Muntz was a member of the [[Ontario Society of Artists]] starting in 1891; she was the first woman appointed to its Executive Council in 1899, serving until 1903.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" />\n\nFollowing the death of her sister in 1915, she returned to Toronto and married her brother-in-law Charles W.B. Lyall to care for the children of her sister's marriage (there were 11 of them but only two remained at home). She then set a studio up in the attic of their home, and started signing her works with her married name.<ref name=Prakesh /> In 1930, Muntz was ill and dying of Exophthalmic Goitre brought on partly by overwork and worry about the family responsibilities she had assumed fifteen years earlier.{{sfn|Murray|2012|p=48}} Despite these trying personal circumstances, she continued to paint until her death in 1930.<ref name=Prakesh />\n\nLyall is interred in the [[Mount Pleasant Cemetery, Toronto|Mount Pleasant Cemetery]] in Toronto.<ref>Find A Grave, [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8044763 Laura Muntz Lyall]</ref>\n\n==Paintings==\n<center>\n<gallery mode=trandional heights=\"185px\">\nFile:Laura Muntz Lyall - Oriental Poppies.jpg|''Oriental Poppies''\nFile:Laura Muntz Lyall - Portrait of a Young Woman.jpg|''Portrait of a young woman''\nFile:Laura Muntz-Lyall \u2013 Young Girl Holding Daffodils.jpg|''Young girl holding daffodils''\nFile:Laura-Muntz-Lyall-The-Little-Red-Hair.jpg|''The little red hair''\nFile:Trees by the River, 1900, by Laura Muntz-Lyall.jpg|''Trees by the river'' (1900)\nFile:Laura Muntz Lyall - Interesting Story - Google Art Project.jpg|''Interesting Story'' (1898)\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{Cite book\n|title=Laura Muntz Lyall: Impressions of Women and Childhood\n|last=Murray\n|first=Joan\n|author-link=Joan Murray (art historian)\n|publisher=Boardwalk Ventures Inc. by McGill Queen's University Press\n|year=2012\n|isbn=978-0-7735-4098-9\n|location=Montreal, Quebec\n|ref=harv\n|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=RE_uugAACAAJ&dq\n}}\n\n== Further Reading ==\n* Prakash, A.K. Impressionism in Canada: A Journey of Rediscovery. Stuttgart: Arnoldsche Art Publishers, 2015, pp. 418-437. {{ISBN |978-3-89790-427-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artist.php?iartistid=3399 Works by Laura Muntz Lyall at the National Gallery of Canada]\n* [https://archive.is/20130115185131/http://www.myhamilton.ca/articles/laura-muntz-lyall-1860-1930 Laura Muntz Lyall (1860 - 1930)] at [http://www.myhamilton.ca/ myHamilton.ca]\n\n{{Impressionists}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyall, Laura Muntz}}\n[[Category:Canadian Impressionist painters]]\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian women painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women artists]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi alumni]]\n[[Category:Associates of the Royal College of Art]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour = \n| name        = Laura Muntz Lyall\n| image       = Photo of Laura Muntz Lyall.jpg \n| caption     =  \n| birth_name  = Laura Adeline Muntz\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1860|6|18|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = Leamington Spa, Warwickshire, United Kingdom\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1930|12|9|1860|6|18|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = Toronto, Ontario, Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| education   = Ontario School of Art, Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi\n| spouse      = Charles W.B. Lyall\n| field       = Painting\n| training    = \n| movement    = [[Impressionism]]\n}}\n\n'''Laura Muntz Lyall''' ([[Leamington Spa, Warwickshire]], June 18, 1860 &ndash; [[Toronto]] December 9, 1930) was a Canadian impressionist painter, known for her portrayal of mothers and children.<ref name=CWAHI>{{cite web|title=LYALL, Laura Muntz|work=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=38|publisher=Concordia University|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nBorn '''Laura Adeline Muntz''' in Leamington Spa, [[Warwickshire]], [[England]] in 1860,{{sfn|Murray|2012|p=133}} her family emigrated to Canada when she was a child.<ref name=\"FromWomensEyes\">{{cite book|last1=Farr|first1=Dorothy|last2=Luckyj|first2=Natalie|title=From Women's Eyes: Women Painters in Canada|date=1975|publisher=Agnes Etherington Art Centre|location=Kingston|pages=28}}</ref> She grew up on a farm in the [[Muskoka|Muskoka District]] of [[Ontario]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> As a young woman, Muntz`s interest in art led to her take lessons in painting from [[William Charles Forster]] of Hamilton and to live and work at his school.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /><ref name=Prakesh /> Starting in 1882, she began to take classes at the [[OCAD_University#History|Ontario School of Art]] where she studied with [[Lucius Richard O'Brien]], and later under [[George Agnew Reid]].<ref name=Prakesh>{{cite book | title=Independent Spirit: Early Canadian Women Artists | publisher=Firefly Books | author=Prakash, A.K. | year=2008 | location=Buffalo, New York | pages=265\u2013268 | isbn=1554074177}}</ref> She studied briefly at the South Kensington School of Art in 1887, then returned to Canada to continue her studies with Reid.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> In 1891, she embarked on a seven-year period of study in Paris, France, with excursions to study the works of [[Michelangelo]] and other artists where she was influenced by the [[Impressionism|impressionist]] style. While in Paris, she studied at the renowned [[Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi]], and her work was exhibited in various exhibitions, resulting in some works being reproduced in French periodicals. On her return to Canada in 1898, she set up a studio in [[Toronto]] and began to take students.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" />  She would later move to Montreal to continue her art career at 6 Beaver Hall Square.<ref name=Prakesh />\n\nHer work received recognition both in Canada and beyond. Muntz Lyall  exhibited her work at the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Palace of Fine Arts]] at the 1893 [[World's Columbian Exposition]] in [[Chicago]], Illinois,<ref name=\"Nichols\">{{cite web |last1=Nichols |first1=K. L. |title=Women's Art at the World's Columbian Fair & Exposition, Chicago 1893| url=http://arcadiasystems.org/academia/cassatt9e.html#lyall|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> and then in 1894 as part of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Artistes Fran\u00e7ais]] in Paris.  Lyall continued to exhibit at many international exhibitions following her return from Paris, and her work was recognized with a silver medal at the 1901 [[Pan-American Exposition]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\">{{Cite book|title = The Woman as Artist and as Subject in Canadian Painting|last = Gualtieri|first = Julia|publisher = Queen's University|year = 1989|isbn = |location = Kingston, Ontario|pages = 145\u2013146, 155\u2013161}}</ref> She was subsequently awarded a bronze medal at the 1904 [[Louisiana Purchase Exposition|St Louis World Fair Exposition]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /><ref name=Prakesh />  She showed 27 paintings with the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts between 1893 and 1929.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" />  Her work was frequently compared and contrasted with that of her contemporary and friend [[Florence Carlyle]].<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> Both the [[National Gallery of Canada]] and the [[Art Gallery of Ontario]] include her works in their holdings.<ref name=CWAHI />\n\nShe was elected as a member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]<ref name=\"RCA1880\">{{cite web|title=Members since 1880|url=http://rca-arc.ca/who-we-are/members/members-since-1880/|publisher=Royal Canadian Academy of Arts|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> in 1896, only the eighth woman to receive this honour.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" /> Muntz was a member of the [[Ontario Society of Artists]] starting in 1891; she was the first woman appointed to its Executive Council in 1899, serving until 1903.<ref name=\"Gualtieri\" />\n\nFollowing the death of her sister in 1915, she returned to Toronto and married her brother-in-law Charles W.B. Lyall to care for the children of her sister's marriage (there were 11 of them but some had left home). She then set a studio up in the attic of their home, and started signing her works with her married name.<ref name=Prakesh /> In 1930, Muntz was ill and dying of Exophthalmic Goitre brought on partly by overwork and worry about the family responsibilities she had assumed fifteen years earlier.{{sfn|Murray|2012|p=48}} Despite these trying personal circumstances, she continued to paint until her death in 1930.<ref name=Prakesh />\n\nLyall is interred in the [[Mount Pleasant Cemetery, Toronto|Mount Pleasant Cemetery]] in Toronto.<ref>Find A Grave, [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8044763 Laura Muntz Lyall]</ref>\n\n==Paintings==\n<center>\n<gallery mode=trandional heights=\"185px\">\nFile:Laura Muntz Lyall - Oriental Poppies.jpg|''Oriental Poppies''\nFile:Laura Muntz Lyall - Portrait of a Young Woman.jpg|''Portrait of a young woman''\nFile:Laura Muntz-Lyall \u2013 Young Girl Holding Daffodils.jpg|''Young girl holding daffodils''\nFile:Laura-Muntz-Lyall-The-Little-Red-Hair.jpg|''The little red hair''\nFile:Trees by the River, 1900, by Laura Muntz-Lyall.jpg|''Trees by the river'' (1900)\nFile:Laura Muntz Lyall - Interesting Story - Google Art Project.jpg|''Interesting Story'' (1898)\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{Cite book\n|title=Laura Muntz Lyall: Impressions of Women and Childhood\n|last=Murray\n|first=Joan\n|author-link=Joan Murray (art historian)\n|publisher=Boardwalk Ventures Inc. by McGill Queen's University Press\n|year=2012\n|isbn=978-0-7735-4098-9\n|location=Montreal, Quebec\n|ref=harv\n|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=RE_uugAACAAJ&dq\n}}\n\n== Further Reading ==\n* Prakash, A.K. Impressionism in Canada: A Journey of Rediscovery. Stuttgart: Arnoldsche Art Publishers, 2015, pp. 418-437. {{ISBN |978-3-89790-427-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artist.php?iartistid=3399 Works by Laura Muntz Lyall at the National Gallery of Canada]\n* [https://archive.is/20130115185131/http://www.myhamilton.ca/articles/laura-muntz-lyall-1860-1930 Laura Muntz Lyall (1860 - 1930)] at [http://www.myhamilton.ca/ myHamilton.ca]\n\n{{Impressionists}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyall, Laura Muntz}}\n[[Category:Canadian Impressionist painters]]\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian women painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women artists]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi alumni]]\n[[Category:Associates of the Royal College of Art]]\n", "name_user": "Joan arden murray", "label": "safe", "comment": "fleshed out Muntz`s period in Paris", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Muntz_Lyall"}
